{"title_page": "Arbitrium", "text_new": "{{short description|Viral peptide for communication}}\n\n'''Arbitrium''' is a [[virus|viral]] [[peptide]] produced by [[Bacteriophage|bacteriophages]] to communicate with each other.<ref name = ElieDolgin2019>{{Cite journal | last1 = Dolgin | first1 = Elie | doi = 10.1038/d41586-019-01880-6| title = The secret social lives of viruses | journal = Nature | volume = 570 | issue = 7761 | pages = 290\u2013292 | year = 2019 | pmid = 31213694| pmc =}}</ref> It is six [[amino acid]]s long, and is produced when a phage infects a bacterial host. It signals to other phages that a host has been infected.\n\n==Discovery==\nArbitrium was first observed by a team led by Rotem Sorek, a microbial geneticist at the [[Weizmann Institute of Science]] in [[Israel]].<ref name = EwenCallaway2017>{{Cite journal | last1 = Callaway | first1 = Ewen | doi = 10.1038/nature.2017.21313 | doi-access= free | url = https://www.nature.com/news/do-you-speak-virus-phages-caught-sending-chemical-messages-1.21313 | title = Do you speak virus? Phages caught sending chemical messages | journal = Nature | volume = | pages = | year = 2017 | pmid = | pmc =}}</ref><ref name=\"Erez2017\">{{cite journal | last=Erez | first=Zohar | last2=Steinberger-Levy | first2=Ida | last3=Shamir | first3=Maya | last4=Doron | first4=Shany | last5=Stokar-Avihail | first5=Avigail | last6=Peleg | first6=Yoav | last7=Melamed | first7=Sarah | last8=Leavitt | first8=Azita | last9=Savidor | first9=Alon | last10=Albeck | first10=Shira | last11=Amitai | first11=Gil | last12=Sorek | first12=Rotem | title=Communication between viruses guides lysis\u2013lysogeny decisions | journal=Nature | volume=541 | issue=7638 | date=2017-01-26 | issn=0028-0836 | pmid=28099413 | pmc=5378303 | doi=10.1038/nature21049 | pages=488\u2013493}}</ref> They were studying communication in ''[[Bacillus subtilis]]'' bacteria - in particular, how bacteria infected with phages warn nearby uninfected bacteria about the presence of these viruses. They found that the phages (strain phi3T) communicated with each other to co-ordinate their infection.<ref name = ElieDolgin2019/>\n\n==Mechanism==\nMany phages, known as [[Temperateness (virology)|temperate phages]],  when they infect a bacterium,  may enter either the [[lytic]] or the [[lysogenic]] pathway. The lytic pathway causes the host to produce and release a large number of daughter phages, usually killing it in the process. The lysogenic pathway involves the virus inserting its genome into the bacterium's. At a later stage, the viral genome is activated, and it continues along the lytic pathway of producing several daughter phages.\n\nArbitrium is used by at least some phages to decide how common fresh hosts are. Each infection causes the production of some arbitrium, and the remaining phages gauge the concentration of arbitrium around them. If the arbitrium concentration is too high, it may indicate that uninfected hosts are running out. The viruses then switch from lysis to lysogeny, so as to not deplete all available hosts.<ref name = ElieDolgin2019/>\n\nAccording to a team led by Alberto Marina at the Biomedical Institute of Valencia in Spain, also studying the ''Bacillus subtilis/'' SPbeta phage system, arbitrium (AimP) binds to the AimX [[transcription factor]] AimR, and suppresses the activity of AimX, a negative regulator of lysogeny.<ref name = GallegodelSol2019>{{Cite journal | last1 = Gallego del Sol | first1 = Francisca |  last2 = Penad\u00e9s | first2 = Jos\u00e9 R. |  last3 = Marina | first3 = Alberto | doi = 10.1016/j.molcel.2019.01.025 | doi-access= free | url = https://www.cell.com/molecular-cell/fulltext/S1097-2765(19)30045-0 | title = Deciphering the Molecular Mechanism Underpinning Phage Arbitrium Communication Systems | journal = Molecular Cell | volume = 74 |issue = 1 | pages = 59\u201372 | year = 2019 | pmid = 30745087| pmc =6458997}}</ref><ref name = ZeyuanGuan2019>{{Cite journal | last1 = Guan | first1 = Zeyuan |display-authors = etal | doi = 10.1038/s41421-019-0101-2 | doi-access= free | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/s41421-019-0101-2.pdf | title = Structural insights into DNA recognition by AimR of the arbitrium communication system in the SPbeta phage | journal = Cell Discovery | volume = 5 | pages = 29\u2013 | year = 2019 | pmid = 31149347| pmc =}}</ref><ref> Dou C, Xiong J, Gu Y, Yin K, Wang J, Hu Y, Zhou D, Fu X, Qi S, Zhu X, Yao S. Structural and functional insights into the regulation of the lysis\u2013lysogeny decision in viral communities. Nature microbiology. 2018 Nov;3(11):1285.</ref> Marina has also shown in the same  system that the virus's arbitrium receptor interacts not only with bacterial genes that help it reproduce, but also with several other stretches of DNA. He has suggested that arbitrium signals may be able to alter the activity of important bacterial genes.<ref name=\"ElieDolgin2019\" />\n\nMore recently, another team at the Sorek lab, headed by Avigail Stokar-Avihail and Nitzan Tal, has shown similar systems in other species of Bacilllus bacteria, the pathogenic species ''[[Bacillus anthracis]]'', ''[[Bacillus cereus]]'', and ''[[Bacillus thuringiensis]].''  <ref name=Tal1>Stokar-Avihail A, Tal N, Erez Z, Lopatina A, Sorek R. Widespread Utilization of Peptide Communication in Phages Infecting Soil and Pathogenic Bacteria. ''Cell host & microbe''. 2019 May 8;25(5):746-55.</ref>  They speculate that \"the occurrence of peptide-based communication systems among phages more broadly remains to be explored.\" <ref name=Tal1 />\n\n==Applications==\nSorek has suggested that since human viruses like HIV and herpes can cause active and latent infections, they might be using an arbitrium-like system to communicate. In this case, that analogue could be used to suppress infections by making the viruses completely latent.<ref name = ElieDolgin2019/><ref name = EwenCallaway2017/> Prof. [[Martha Clokie]], of the [[University of Leicester]], has hailed the discovery of viral communication as 'transformative'.<ref name = EwenCallaway2017/>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Evolutionary biology|Science|Viruses}}\n* [[Quorum sensing]] - the corresponding phenomenon in bacteria\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Virus topics}}\n\n[[Category:Viral proteins]]\n\n\n{{protein-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Genetic mechanism in bacteriohages}}\n\n'''Arbitrium''' is a [[virus|viral]] [[peptide]] produced by [[Bacteriophage|bacteriophages]] to communicate with each other.<ref name = ElieDolgin2019>{{Cite journal | last1 = Dolgin | first1 = Elie | doi = 10.1038/d41586-019-01880-6| title = The secret social lives of viruses | journal = Nature | volume = 570 | issue = 7761 | pages = 290\u2013292 | year = 2019 | pmid = 31213694| pmc =}}</ref> It is six [[amino acid]]s long, and is produced when a phage infects a bacterial host. It signals to other phages that a host has been infected.\n\n==Discovery==\nArbitrium was first observed by a team led by Rotem Sorek, a microbial geneticist at the [[Weizmann Institute of Science]] in [[Israel]].<ref name = EwenCallaway2017>{{Cite journal | last1 = Callaway | first1 = Ewen | doi = 10.1038/nature.2017.21313 | doi-access= free | url = https://www.nature.com/news/do-you-speak-virus-phages-caught-sending-chemical-messages-1.21313 | title = Do you speak virus? Phages caught sending chemical messages | journal = Nature | volume = | pages = | year = 2017 | pmid = | pmc =}}</ref><ref name=\"Erez2017\">{{cite journal | last=Erez | first=Zohar | last2=Steinberger-Levy | first2=Ida | last3=Shamir | first3=Maya | last4=Doron | first4=Shany | last5=Stokar-Avihail | first5=Avigail | last6=Peleg | first6=Yoav | last7=Melamed | first7=Sarah | last8=Leavitt | first8=Azita | last9=Savidor | first9=Alon | last10=Albeck | first10=Shira | last11=Amitai | first11=Gil | last12=Sorek | first12=Rotem | title=Communication between viruses guides lysis\u2013lysogeny decisions | journal=Nature | volume=541 | issue=7638 | date=2017-01-26 | issn=0028-0836 | pmid=28099413 | pmc=5378303 | doi=10.1038/nature21049 | pages=488\u2013493}}</ref> They were studying communication in ''[[Bacillus subtilis]]'' bacteria - in particular, how bacteria infected with phages warn nearby uninfected bacteria about the presence of these viruses. They found that the phages (strain phi3T) communicated with each other to co-ordinate their infection.<ref name = ElieDolgin2019/>\n\n==Mechanism==\nMany phages, known as [[Temperateness (virology)|temperate phages]],  when they infect a bacterium,  may enter either the [[lytic]] or the [[lysogenic]] pathway. The lytic pathway causes the host to produce and release a large number of daughter phages, usually killing it in the process. The lysogenic pathway involves the virus inserting its genome into the bacterium's. At a later stage, the viral genome is activated, and it continues along the lytic pathway of producing several daughter phages.\n\nArbitrium is used by at least some phages to decide how common fresh hosts are. Each infection causes the production of some arbitrium, and the remaining phages gauge the concentration of arbitrium around them. If the arbitrium concentration is too high, it may indicate that uninfected hosts are running out. The viruses then switch from lysis to lysogeny, so as to not deplete all available hosts.<ref name = ElieDolgin2019/>\n\nAccording to a team led by Alberto Marina at the Biomedical Institute of Valencia in Spain, also studying the ''Bacillus subtilis/'' SPbeta phage system, arbitrium (AimP) binds to the AimX [[transcription factor]] AimR, and suppresses the activity of AimX, a negative regulator of lysogeny.<ref name = GallegodelSol2019>{{Cite journal | last1 = Gallego del Sol | first1 = Francisca |  last2 = Penad\u00e9s | first2 = Jos\u00e9 R. |  last3 = Marina | first3 = Alberto | doi = 10.1016/j.molcel.2019.01.025 | doi-access= free | url = https://www.cell.com/molecular-cell/fulltext/S1097-2765(19)30045-0 | title = Deciphering the Molecular Mechanism Underpinning Phage Arbitrium Communication Systems | journal = Molecular Cell | volume = 74 |issue = 1 | pages = 59\u201372 | year = 2019 | pmid = 30745087| pmc =6458997}}</ref><ref name = ZeyuanGuan2019>{{Cite journal | last1 = Guan | first1 = Zeyuan |display-authors = etal | doi = 10.1038/s41421-019-0101-2 | doi-access= free | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/s41421-019-0101-2.pdf | title = Structural insights into DNA recognition by AimR of the arbitrium communication system in the SPbeta phage | journal = Cell Discovery | volume = 5 | pages = 29\u2013 | year = 2019 | pmid = 31149347| pmc =}}</ref><ref> Dou C, Xiong J, Gu Y, Yin K, Wang J, Hu Y, Zhou D, Fu X, Qi S, Zhu X, Yao S. Structural and functional insights into the regulation of the lysis\u2013lysogeny decision in viral communities. Nature microbiology. 2018 Nov;3(11):1285.</ref> Marina has also shown in the same  system that the virus's arbitrium receptor interacts not only with bacterial genes that help it reproduce, but also with several other stretches of DNA. He has suggested that arbitrium signals may be able to alter the activity of important bacterial genes.<ref name=\"ElieDolgin2019\" />\n\nMore recently, another team at the Sorek lab, headed by Avigail Stokar-Avihail and Nitzan Tal, has shown similar systems in other species of Bacilllus bacteria, the pathogenic species ''[[Bacillus anthracis]]'', ''[[Bacillus cereus]]'', and ''[[Bacillus thuringiensis]].''  <ref name=Tal1>Stokar-Avihail A, Tal N, Erez Z, Lopatina A, Sorek R. Widespread Utilization of Peptide Communication in Phages Infecting Soil and Pathogenic Bacteria. ''Cell host & microbe''. 2019 May 8;25(5):746-55.</ref>  They speculate that \"the occurrence of peptide-based communication systems among phages more broadly remains to be explored.\" <ref name=Tal1 />\n\n==Applications==\nSorek has suggested that since human viruses like HIV and herpes can cause active and latent infections, they might be using an arbitrium-like system to communicate. In this case, that analogue could be used to suppress infections by making the viruses completely latent.<ref name = ElieDolgin2019/><ref name = EwenCallaway2017/> Prof. [[Martha Clokie]], of the [[University of Leicester]], has hailed the discovery of viral communication as 'transformative'.<ref name = EwenCallaway2017/>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Evolutionary biology|Science|Viruses}}\n* [[Quorum sensing]] - the corresponding phenomenon in bacteria\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Virus topics}}\n\n[[Category:Viral proteins]]\n\n\n{{protein-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tridwoxi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changingshort descriptionfrom \"Genetic mechanism in bacteriohages\" to \"Viral peptide for communication\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arbitrium"}
{"title_page": "Kalyani Nagar", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Kalyani Nagar\n| official_name                   = \n| native_name                     = \u0915\u0932\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0928\u0917\u0930\n| native_name_lang                = mr\n| settlement_type                 = Neighbourhood\n| image_skyline                   = Gold Big Cinemas.jpg\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{IND}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = City\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_name2               = Pune\n| governing_body                  = Pune Municipal Corporation\n| population_total                = 25272\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| postal_code                     = 411006\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n\n'''Kalyani Nagar''' is a predominantly affluent residential [[neighbourhood]] located in eastern [[Pune]], [[India]]. It has a population of 25,272 according to the [[2011 Census of India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmc.gov.in/sites/default/files/census-population-data-2011.pdf|title=Data of Census 2011- Pune Municipal Corporation|publisher=Census of India|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref> The locality is administered by the Nagar Road-Wadgaonsheri Ward Office of the [[Pune Municipal Corporation]].\n\nThe neighbourhood is the location of the [[Aga Khan Palace]], a historical landmark of national importance, where [[Mahatma Gandhi]] was imprisoned between 1942 and 1945.\n\n== History ==\nKalyani Nagar is named after Neelkanth Kalyani,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.virtualpune.com/html/localguide/cityfacts/html/kalyani_nagar.shtml | title=Pune City Facts | work=www.virtualpune.com | accessdate=2007-12-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107202742/http://www.virtualpune.com/html/localguide/cityfacts/html/kalyani_nagar.shtml | archive-date=7 November 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> one of the city's foremost industrialists, who founded the [[Kalyani Group|Kalyani Forging Company]] in the early 1960s.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2005/1226/052A.html | title=Forging Ahead | work=Anuradha Raghunathan - www.forbes.com | accessdate=2007-12-18 | date=2005-12-26}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cerebrum IT Park B2 Building.jpg|thumb]]\nAlthough primarily a [[residential]] locality, rapid development and improved accessibility over the years, the developed society is '''sunshine court society''' opp HDFC bank. '''sky lounge.''' particularly due to the construction of the H. H. Aga Khan Bridge across the [[Mula-Mutha River]] has seen the emergence of many new buildings, commercial construction, and information technology parks. Cerebrum IT park is located in the neighbourhood.\n\nTechnology centres owned by multinational companies such as [[HSBC]], [[Capgemini]] and [[Cybage]] now account for much of the non-retail commercial activity in the neighbourhood.also kalyani nagar is the top area to live in, many amenities and are devloped in.\n\n== Location ==\n<mapframe latitude=\"18.548138\" longitude=\"73.90254\" zoom=\"14\" width=\"282\" height=\"136\" align=\"right\" />Geographically, Kalyani Nagar is bounded on the south by the [[Mula-Mutha River]], which divides the city of Pune into two. Across the riverbank to the south is [[Koregaon Park]], an upscale neighbourhood known for the [[Osho International|Osho International Meditation Resort]].\n\nKalyani Nagar is situated 5&nbsp;kilometres from [[Pune Junction railway station]] and 4&nbsp;kilometres from [[Pune Airport]]. Limited mass public transportation is available within the neighbourhood. Instead, [[Auto rickshaw|auto-rickshaws]] and ride-share services are used as a means of public transport.\n\nThe [[Pune Metro]] is planned to pass through the locality, and a metro station may be constructed on East Avenue. However, construction through the neighbourhood is controversial, due to its planned displacement of trees and wildlife of the [[Salim Ali Bird Sanctuary]], alleged failure to follow due process, and the possibility of added traffic congestion. In November 2018, citizens protested construction of the [[Pune Metro]] through Kalyani Nagar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/residents-oppose-plan-to-take-metro-through-kalyaninagar/articleshow/66493098.cms|title=Residents oppose plan to take Metro through Kalyaninagar|date=2018-11-04|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|18.5481|73.9033|type:landmark_source:enwiki-googlemaplink|display=title}}\n{{Pune topics}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Pune]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Kalyani Nagar\n| official_name                   = \n| native_name                     = \u0915\u0932\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0928\u0917\u0930\n| native_name_lang                = mr\n| settlement_type                 = Neighbourhood\n| image_skyline                   = Gold Big Cinemas.jpg\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{IND}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = City\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_name2               = Pune\n| governing_body                  = Pune Municipal Corporation\n| population_total                = 25272\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| postal_code                     = 411006\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n\n'''Kalyani Nagar''' is a predominantly affluent residential [[neighbourhood]] located in eastern [[Pune]], [[India]]. It has a population of 25,272 according to the [[2011 Census of India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmc.gov.in/sites/default/files/census-population-data-2011.pdf|title=Data of Census 2011- Pune Municipal Corporation|publisher=Census of India|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref> The locality is administered by the Nagar Road-Wadgaonsheri Ward Office of the [[Pune Municipal Corporation]].\n\nThe neighbourhood is the location of the [[Aga Khan Palace]], a historical landmark of national importance, where [[Mahatma Gandhi]] was imprisoned between 1942 and 1945.\n\n== History ==\nKalyani Nagar is named after Neelkanth Kalyani,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.virtualpune.com/html/localguide/cityfacts/html/kalyani_nagar.shtml | title=Pune City Facts | work=www.virtualpune.com | accessdate=2007-12-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107202742/http://www.virtualpune.com/html/localguide/cityfacts/html/kalyani_nagar.shtml | archive-date=7 November 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> one of the city's foremost industrialists, who founded the [[Kalyani Group|Kalyani Forging Company]] in the early 1960s.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2005/1226/052A.html | title=Forging Ahead | work=Anuradha Raghunathan - www.forbes.com | accessdate=2007-12-18 | date=2005-12-26}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cerebrum IT Park B2 Building.jpg|thumb|Sunset View from Cerebrum IT Park B3 Building 7th Floor]]\nAlthough primarily a [[residential]] locality, rapid development and improved accessibility over the years, the developed society is sunshine court. particularly due to the construction of the H. H. Aga Khan Bridge across the [[Mula-Mutha River]] has seen the emergence of many new buildings, commercial construction, and information technology parks. Cerebrum IT park is located in the neighbourhood.\n\nTechnology centres owned by multinational companies such as [[HSBC]], [[Capgemini]] and [[Cybage]] now account for much of the non-retail commercial activity in the neighbourhood.also kalyani nagar is the top area to live in, many amenities and societies are there like trump towers, sun shines court, sky lounge.\n\n== Location ==\n<mapframe latitude=\"18.548138\" longitude=\"73.90254\" zoom=\"14\" width=\"282\" height=\"136\" align=\"right\" />Geographically, Kalyani Nagar is bounded on the south by the [[Mula-Mutha River]], which divides the city of Pune into two. Across the riverbank to the south is [[Koregaon Park]], an upscale neighbourhood known for the [[Osho International|Osho International Meditation Resort]].\n\nKalyani Nagar is situated 5&nbsp;kilometres from [[Pune Junction railway station]] and 4&nbsp;kilometres from [[Pune Airport]]. Limited mass public transportation is available within the neighbourhood. Instead, [[Auto rickshaw|auto-rickshaws]] and ride-share services are used as a means of public transport.\n\nThe [[Pune Metro]] is planned to pass through the locality, and a metro station may be constructed on East Avenue. However, construction through the neighbourhood is controversial, due to its planned displacement of trees and wildlife of the [[Salim Ali Bird Sanctuary]], alleged failure to follow due process, and the possibility of added traffic congestion. In November 2018, citizens protested construction of the [[Pune Metro]] through Kalyani Nagar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/residents-oppose-plan-to-take-metro-through-kalyaninagar/articleshow/66493098.cms|title=Residents oppose plan to take Metro through Kalyaninagar|date=2018-11-04|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|18.5481|73.9033|type:landmark_source:enwiki-googlemaplink|display=title}}\n{{Pune topics}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Pune]]\n", "name_user": "Vishwajit9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(the information)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalyani_Nagar"}
{"title_page": "Borle\u0219ti", "text_new": "{{about||the village in Alba County|C\u00e2mpeni|the village in Arge\u0219 County|Meri\u0219ani|the village in Satu Mare County|Pomi}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Neam\u021b\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Neam\u021b County\n|coordinates = {{coord|46.777|N|26.505|E|region:RO|display=title}}\n|name=Borle\u0219ti\n|image_map              = Borle\u0219ti in the Neam\u021b County.svg\n}}\n'''Borle\u0219ti''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Neam\u021b County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of five villages: Borle\u0219ti, Nechit, Mastac\u0103n, Ruseni and \u0218ovoaia.\n\n{{Neam\u0163 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borlesti}}\n[[Category:Communes in Neam\u021b County]]\n\n{{Neam\u0163-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about||the village in Alba County|C\u00e2mpeni|the village in Arge\u0219 County|Meri\u0219ani|the village in Satu Mare County|Pomi}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Neam\u021b\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Neam\u021b County\n|coordinates = {{coord|46.777|N|26.505|E|region:RO|display=title}}\n|name=Borle\u0219ti\n|image_map=\n}}\n'''Borle\u0219ti''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Neam\u021b County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of five villages: Borle\u0219ti, Nechit, Mastac\u0103n, Ruseni and \u0218ovoaia.\n\n{{Neam\u0163 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borlesti}}\n[[Category:Communes in Neam\u021b County]]\n\n{{Neam\u0163-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Borle%C8%99ti"}
{"title_page": "Perri \"Pebbles\" Reid", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name         = Perri \"Pebbles\" Reid\n|image        =\n|caption      = Pebbles\n|background   = solo_singer\n|birth_name   = Perri Arlette McKissack<ref name=\"people\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20100090,00.html |title=No Neanderthal, Pebbles Is Now a Yabba-Dabba-Do Pop Success |date=3 October 1988 |journal=[[People (magazine)|People]] |issn=0093-7673}}</ref>\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1964|08|29}}<ref name=\"yob\">[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VLPB-4SN Year of birth confirmation], Familysearch.org; accessed April 7, 2015.</ref>\n|birth_place  = [[Oakland, California]], U.S.\n| alias = {{hlist|Pebbles|Perri|Peb|P.}}\n|genre        = {{hlist|[[Dance-pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[new jack swing]]|[[urban contemporary]]}} \n|occupation =  {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|businesswoman|music executive|producer}}\n|years_active = {{ubl|1980\u2013present}}\n|label        = {{hlist|[[Music Corporation of America|MCA]]|[[Savvy Records|Savvy]]|[[Perspective Records|Perspective]]|Pebbitone, Inc}}\n|associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]]|[[Cherrelle]]|[[Karyn White]]|[[L.A. Reid]]|[[P.A. (group)|P.A.]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Perri Arlette Reid''' (n\u00e9e '''McKissack'''; August 29, 1964), professionally known by her former stage name, '''Pebbles''', is an American [[recording artist|singer-songwriter]], businesswoman, producer and music executive. Reid is perhaps best known for her hit songs during the late 1980s and early 1990s such as \"[[Girlfriend (Pebbles song)|Girlfriend]]\" (1987), \"[[Mercedes Boy]]\" (1988) and \"[[Giving You the Benefit]]\" (1990). In addition to a recording career, Reid created the [[contemporary R&B]] group [[TLC (group)|TLC]]. Reid is currently an [[Atlanta]]-based minister, known as \"Sister Perri\".\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nReid was born Perri Arlette McKissack on August 29, 1964,<ref name=\"Jet\"/><ref name=soul>{{cite book |last=Gregory |first=Hugh |title=Soul Music A-Z |page=[https://archive.org/details/soulmusicaz00greg/page/235 235] |publisher=[[Da Capo Press]] |year=1995 |isbn=978-0306806438 |url=https://archive.org/details/soulmusicaz00greg/page/235 }}</ref><ref name=Warner>{{cite book|last=Warner|first=Jay|url={{Google books|eyfeVZ6jf1oC|On This Day in Black Music History|page=243|plainurl=no}}|title=On This Day in Black Music History|page=243|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|year=2006|isbn=9780634099267}}</ref> one of four siblings to two mixed African-American parents. Reid's parents divorced when she was around six years old. Her mother raised Reid and her siblings on the income of a waitress and housekeeper. Reid got her start at age sixteen in 1981 as a [[backing vocalist]] for the percussionist/band leader Bill Summers and the funk band [[Con Funk Shun]]. Reid co-wrote one of Con Funk Shun's singles, \"Body Lovers\".<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Con-Funk-Shun-Body-Lovers/release/2088370 \"Body Lovers\"], discogs.com; accessed April 7, 2015.</ref> At age nineteen, a local musician gave Reid a production deal which fell through several months later when she became pregnant with her daughter.<ref name=\"people\"/> While working at an [[Oakland, California]], real estate office she met contractor George L. Smith. Smith bankrolled Pebbles with $80,000 for a demo tape and video for \"[[Mercedes Boy]]\". The demo and video led to a contract with MCA.<ref name=\"people\"/> She recorded several hit singles on her own during the late 1980s and early 1990s, including \"[[Girlfriend (Pebbles song)|Girlfriend]]\", \"[[Mercedes Boy]]\", \"[[Giving You the Benefit]]\", and \"[[Love Makes Things Happen]]\".<ref name=\"billboard albums\">{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=pebbles|chart=all}}|title=US Album Charts > Pebbles|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2012-04-21}}</ref> Reid's cousin is R&B singer [[Cherrelle]] who was featured, along with [[Johnny Gill]], on her 1991 hit song, \"Always\".\n\n===Pebbitone and TLC===\nIn July 1989, Pebbles formed the [[Atlanta]]-based production company Pebbitone and founded her own record label, [[Savvy Records]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/479/000045344/|title=Pebbles|website=Nndb.com|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref> Pebbitone the greedy b.t.. managed [[TLC (group)|TLC]], which was signed with [[LaFace Records]], L.A. Reid's record label.<ref name = \"nymag\">{{cite web|last=Tannenbaum|first=Rob|title=L.A. Comes to New York|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/music/features/4318/index2.html|work=New York|accessdate=2011-07-07}}</ref> When TLC filed for bankruptcy in 1995, due to Pebbles' alleged mismanagement regarding their funds,<ref name=\"Jet\">{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fjkDAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=snippet&q=37%20-page&f=false|title=Singer Pebbles Talks About Breakups With Husband L.A. Reid And Group TLC|journal=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]] |page=37 |date=October 23, 1995|volume=88|number=24|ISSN=0021-5996}}</ref> the ensuing conflict damaged Pebbles' marriage. She divorced Reid, and Pebbitone sued LaFace for $10 million.<ref name=\"Jet\"/>\n\n===Religious conversion===\nIn 1997, Pebbles underwent a religious conversion. Under her new stage name \"Sister Perri\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_11_55/ai_65014620|work=Ebony|title='Sister Perri' The Preacher Formerly Known As Pebbles|year=2000}}</ref> she founded Women of God Changing Lives (WOGCL) Ministries. As an ordained minister, she now preaches and ministers through song.<ref>{{cite journal| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d9oDAAAAMBAJ&q=Sister+Perri|work=Ebony|title='Sister Perri' The Preacher Formerly Known As Pebbles|date=September 1, 2000|last=Kinnon|first=Joy Bennett|pages=108\u2013114|volume=55|number=11|ISSN=0012-9011}}</ref> In 2008, after a thirteen-year music hiatus, Reid released her fourth album and debut gospel album, ''Prophetic Flows Vol I & II'', which peaked at #12 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Gospel Album Chart. In February 2011, she was named the executive producer/host of [[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]'s national R&B search.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=pebbles-mn0000041420 |tab=biography |pure_url=yes}} |title=Pebbles Biography |first=Greg |last=Prato |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://crossroadsnews.com/news/2011/jul/22/lithonia-singer-wins-essence-rb-star-search Lithonia singer wins ''Essence'' R&B Star Search] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20140501165750/http://crossroadsnews.com/news/2011/jul/22/lithonia-singer-wins-essence-rb-star-search |date=2014-05-01 }}, crossroadsnews.com; accessed April 7, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPebbles has been married five times and has two children. Pebbles gave birth to a daughter, Ashley Victoria Winzer, in January 1983. Her first marriage was to her daughter's father from 1983 until 1984. Her second marriage was to [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] contractor George L. Smith from 1985 until 1987. The relationship began as an affair when Smith's wife of twenty years Darlene was battling [[cancer]]. After his wife's passing, 19-year-old Pebbles married 41-year-old Smith, and they made their home in [[San Francisco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/archive/no-neanderthal-pebbles-is-now-a-yabba-dabba-do-pop-success-vol-30-no-14/|title=No Neanderthal, Pebbles Is Now a Yabba-Dabba-Do Pop Success|website=People.com|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref> Smith had a daughter, Jennifer (b. 1972) from his previous marriage. While married, Pebbles began having an affair with [[L.A. Reid]], which led to her divorce from Smith. In July 1989, Pebbles married Reid. They had one son named Aaron, born in 1991. Reid and Pebbles later divorced in 1996. In 2000, Pebbles married former [[MLB]] player [[Otis Nixon]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=20000927&id=S6tAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7yAGAAAAIBAJ&pg=5188,3914825 |title=Otis Nixon and Perri Reid |newspaper=[[Lodi News-Sentinel]] |page=7 |date=27 September 2000}}</ref> They divorced in 2004. Pebbles married her fifth husband Excel Sharieff in 2010, an administrative law judge.\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Pebbles discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Pebbles (Pebbles album)|Pebbles]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Always (Pebbles album)|Always]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Straight from My Heart]]'' (1995)\n* ''Prophetic Flows Vol I & II'' (2008)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|www.sisterperri.com}}\n*{{Discogs artist|83143-Pebbles}}\n*{{IMDb name|1889966}}\n\n{{Pebbles}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reid, Perri}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:New jack swing musicians]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:MCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:American freestyle musicians]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name         = Perri \"Pebbles\" Reid\n|image        =\n|caption      = Pebbles\n|background   = solo_singer\n|birth_name   = Perri Arlette McKissack<ref name=\"people\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20100090,00.html |title=No Neanderthal, Pebbles Is Now a Yabba-Dabba-Do Pop Success |date=3 October 1988 |journal=[[People (magazine)|People]] |issn=0093-7673}}</ref>\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1964|08|29}}<ref name=\"yob\">[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VLPB-4SN Year of birth confirmation], Familysearch.org; accessed April 7, 2015.</ref>\n|birth_place  = [[Oakland, California]], U.S.\n| alias = {{hlist|Pebbles|Perri|Peb|P.}}\n|genre        = {{hlist|[[Dance-pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[new jack swing]]|[[urban contemporary]]}} \n|occupation =  {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|businesswoman|music executive|producer}}\n|years_active = {{ubl|1980\u2013present}}\n|label        = {{hlist|[[Music Corporation of America|MCA]]|[[Savvy Records|Savvy]]|[[Perspective Records|Perspective]]|Pebbitone, Inc}}\n|associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]]|[[Cherrelle]]|[[Karyn White]]|[[L.A. Reid]]|[[P.A. (group)|P.A.]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Perri Arlette Reid''' (n\u00e9e '''McKissack'''; August 29, 1964), professionally known by her former stage name, '''Pebbles''', is an American [[recording artist|singer-songwriter]], businesswoman, producer and music executive. Reid is perhaps best known for her hit songs during the late 1980s and early 1990s such as \"[[Girlfriend (Pebbles song)|Girlfriend]]\" (1987), \"[[Mercedes Boy]]\" (1988) and \"[[Giving You the Benefit]]\" (1990). In addition to a recording career, Reid created the [[contemporary R&B]] group [[TLC (group)|TLC]]. Reid is currently an [[Atlanta]]-based minister, known as \"Sister Perri\".\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nReid was born Perri Arlette McKissack on August 29, 1964,<ref name=\"Jet\"/><ref name=soul>{{cite book |last=Gregory |first=Hugh |title=Soul Music A-Z |page=[https://archive.org/details/soulmusicaz00greg/page/235 235] |publisher=[[Da Capo Press]] |year=1995 |isbn=978-0306806438 |url=https://archive.org/details/soulmusicaz00greg/page/235 }}</ref><ref name=Warner>{{cite book|last=Warner|first=Jay|url={{Google books|eyfeVZ6jf1oC|On This Day in Black Music History|page=243|plainurl=no}}|title=On This Day in Black Music History|page=243|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|year=2006|isbn=9780634099267}}</ref> one of four siblings to two mixed African-American parents. Reid's parents divorced when she was around six years old. Her mother raised Reid and her siblings on the income of a waitress and housekeeper. Reid got her start at age sixteen in 1981 as a [[backing vocalist]] for the percussionist/band leader Bill Summers and the funk band [[Con Funk Shun]]. Reid co-wrote one of Con Funk Shun's singles, \"Body Lovers\".<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Con-Funk-Shun-Body-Lovers/release/2088370 \"Body Lovers\"], discogs.com; accessed April 7, 2015.</ref> At age nineteen, a local musician gave Reid a production deal which fell through several months later when she became pregnant with her daughter.<ref name=\"people\"/> While working at an [[Oakland, California]], real estate office she met contractor George L. Smith. Smith bankrolled Pebbles with $80,000 for a demo tape and video for \"[[Mercedes Boy]]\". The demo and video led to a contract with MCA.<ref name=\"people\"/> She recorded several hit singles on her own during the late 1980s and early 1990s, including \"[[Girlfriend (Pebbles song)|Girlfriend]]\", \"[[Mercedes Boy]]\", \"[[Giving You the Benefit]]\", and \"[[Love Makes Things Happen]]\".<ref name=\"billboard albums\">{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=pebbles|chart=all}}|title=US Album Charts > Pebbles|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2012-04-21}}</ref> Reid's cousin is R&B singer [[Cherrelle]] who was featured, along with [[Johnny Gill]], on her 1991 hit song, \"Always\".\n\n===Pebbitone and TLC===\nIn July 1989, Pebbles formed the [[Atlanta]]-based production company Pebbitone and founded her own record label, [[Savvy Records]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/479/000045344/|title=Pebbles|website=Nndb.com|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref> Pebbitone managed [[TLC (group)|TLC]], which was signed with [[LaFace Records]], L.A. Reid's record label.<ref name = \"nymag\">{{cite web|last=Tannenbaum|first=Rob|title=L.A. Comes to New York|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/music/features/4318/index2.html|work=New York|accessdate=2011-07-07}}</ref> When TLC filed for bankruptcy in 1995, due to Pebbles' alleged mismanagement regarding their funds,<ref name=\"Jet\">{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fjkDAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=snippet&q=37%20-page&f=false|title=Singer Pebbles Talks About Breakups With Husband L.A. Reid And Group TLC|journal=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]] |page=37 |date=October 23, 1995|volume=88|number=24|ISSN=0021-5996}}</ref> the ensuing conflict damaged Pebbles' marriage. She divorced Reid, and Pebbitone sued LaFace for $10 million.<ref name=\"Jet\"/>\n\n===Religious conversion===\nIn 1997, Pebbles underwent a religious conversion. Under her new stage name \"Sister Perri\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_11_55/ai_65014620|work=Ebony|title='Sister Perri' The Preacher Formerly Known As Pebbles|year=2000}}</ref> she founded Women of God Changing Lives (WOGCL) Ministries. As an ordained minister, she now preaches and ministers through song.<ref>{{cite journal| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d9oDAAAAMBAJ&q=Sister+Perri|work=Ebony|title='Sister Perri' The Preacher Formerly Known As Pebbles|date=September 1, 2000|last=Kinnon|first=Joy Bennett|pages=108\u2013114|volume=55|number=11|ISSN=0012-9011}}</ref> In 2008, after a thirteen-year music hiatus, Reid released her fourth album and debut gospel album, ''Prophetic Flows Vol I & II'', which peaked at #12 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Gospel Album Chart. In February 2011, she was named the executive producer/host of [[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]'s national R&B search.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=pebbles-mn0000041420 |tab=biography |pure_url=yes}} |title=Pebbles Biography |first=Greg |last=Prato |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://crossroadsnews.com/news/2011/jul/22/lithonia-singer-wins-essence-rb-star-search Lithonia singer wins ''Essence'' R&B Star Search] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20140501165750/http://crossroadsnews.com/news/2011/jul/22/lithonia-singer-wins-essence-rb-star-search |date=2014-05-01 }}, crossroadsnews.com; accessed April 7, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPebbles has been married five times and has two children. Pebbles gave birth to a daughter, Ashley Victoria Winzer, in January 1983. Her first marriage was to her daughter's father from 1983 until 1984. Her second marriage was to [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] contractor George L. Smith from 1985 until 1987. The relationship began as an affair when Smith's wife of twenty years Darlene was battling [[cancer]]. After his wife's passing, 19-year-old Pebbles married 41-year-old Smith, and they made their home in [[San Francisco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/archive/no-neanderthal-pebbles-is-now-a-yabba-dabba-do-pop-success-vol-30-no-14/|title=No Neanderthal, Pebbles Is Now a Yabba-Dabba-Do Pop Success|website=People.com|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref> Smith had a daughter, Jennifer (b. 1972) from his previous marriage. While married, Pebbles began having an affair with [[L.A. Reid]], which led to her divorce from Smith. In July 1989, Pebbles married Reid. They had one son named Aaron, born in 1991. Reid and Pebbles later divorced in 1996. In 2000, Pebbles married former [[MLB]] player [[Otis Nixon]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=20000927&id=S6tAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7yAGAAAAIBAJ&pg=5188,3914825 |title=Otis Nixon and Perri Reid |newspaper=[[Lodi News-Sentinel]] |page=7 |date=27 September 2000}}</ref> They divorced in 2004. Pebbles married her fifth husband Excel Sharieff in 2010, an administrative law judge.\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Pebbles discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Pebbles (Pebbles album)|Pebbles]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Always (Pebbles album)|Always]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Straight from My Heart]]'' (1995)\n* ''Prophetic Flows Vol I & II'' (2008)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|www.sisterperri.com}}\n*{{Discogs artist|83143-Pebbles}}\n*{{IMDb name|1889966}}\n\n{{Pebbles}}